Hello everyone! I hope you are all doing well!

I know some of you may be wondering what has been going on in the life of me, well between work, the rescue, and training my SDIT Flint I have been rather busy ❤️

In the last little while I have found homes for Milo, Oscar AND Huey which took a little longer than expected but I think they are all now in amazing homes. I have been slowly working through my waitlist for the rescue but it will probably take me a good 2 months  at least to get through the rest. 

I love what I do but man can it be challenging, I’m hanging in there though as there are a lot of birds who need my help ❤️To all my patreons and supporters you rock! 

Happy holidays to everyone and make sure to stay safe this holiday season ❤️

Who’s this? This is Cleo, Eternal Flights newest rehab! 

Cleo has been with one of my lovely fosters for a little bit waiting until I had the time to do a behavioural assessment and book a vet appointment. Amanda is an amazing volunteer that has been working with Cleo on some of her behavioural issues and updating me on her progress, Cleo is a typical conure and full of sass but is definitely not a bird that is going to need a lot of work. As soon as Cleo is cleared by the vet I have no doubt people will be jumping in line to interview for her as she is a very sweet girl. ❤️

My waiting list is slowly getting smaller, I have thankfully been able to rehome directly from some of my fosters which is lovely but I still have many interviews and applications to go through. Can’t wait to work with Cleo as she seems super fun 😄

#parrotrehab #parrotrescue #aww #greencheek #conure #windsorontario

Hello everyone! As you know, Eternal Flight is run on donations! If you would like to support what I do, please consider donating to our new GoFundMe ❤️ many rescues are struggling, with the increase of birds in need our funds are becoming dangerously low once again…If you like what we do please consider donating to the link under my bio ☺️

Your donations allow us to expand and take on more birds in need, they help cover emergency vet visits for new rehabs, allows us to pay for the things the birds who are currently in fosters need, and allows us to provide quality care with the rising costs of living. 

Thank you so much for supporting Eternal Flight ❤️

https://gofund.me/670db4db

Hello everyone long time no chat! For those curious, I have been working steadily away at my waitlist. Nexus a new rescue went for a couple of vet visits, one for a check up and one for blood work, I just got his blood panel results back and he is indeed negative for all that he was tested for and is indeed a boy! 

I know a few of you are probably wondering what the post was about yesterday, unfortunately, a couple rehabs that I had rehomed years prior needed to come back to the rescue. So yesterday I spent most of the day trying to figure out how to get them from Barrie Ontario to Windsor Ontario. Thankfully two amazing new volunteers have donated their time to drive the two birds most of the way! @Corviecat will be taking the two from Barrie Ontario to Toronto and meeting up with the Toronto team @earthybirthyjulie who will be driving from Toronto to London Ontario where @jungle.services will be temporarily boarding them until a good friend and lovely volunteer and I can come up from Windsor Ontario. 

I don’t have to do things like this often, and it is extremely hard and stressful to organize as if something goes wrong the entire thing has to be called off. I am so so thankful for my platform as I would not be able to do things like this if not for the kindness of amazing people across Ontario. 

I appreciate and cherish every one of you, and thank you all from the bottom of my heart for always being willing to not only support the rescue financially, but also volunteer your guys time. 

I wouldn’t be able to do any of this without all of you ❤️ thank you for helping me make a difference in the lives of birds across Ontario.

It’s not often that Eternal Flight reaches out to the public for help but when we do it is always met with such kindness and enthusiasm.

A little while ago I got news that an adoption from years prior was no longer working out, and being that they had moved hours away from me I was unable to get to them so I asked for help and within hours I had so many kind people offering assistance.

Two incredible volunteers drove over 200km (125 miles to my American friends) to bring these birds to London Ontario to stay at @jungle.services until myself and another amazing volunteer can pick them up in a couple days.

A big thank you to Vicki @corviekat (first photo) and Julie @earthybirthyjulie (second photo) for donating their time to help, it is because of the kindness of others that I can continue doing what I do ❤️ I cannot thank you all enough. Also another huge thank you to jungle services for boarding them until I could get out to London! You all rock.

A vent post 

I’m exhausted…I can feel myself being drained and I’m trying my best to stay afloat. I have had three rescues returned from the homes I have placed them in, which quite frankly is very rare but to have it all happening at once is a lot. I love what I do, but rescue work is quite honestly one of the most physically and emotionally draining jobs out there, people don’t see what goes on behind the scenes. They don’t see the hours and hours put into rehabbing, they don’t see the hours put into interviewing, they don’t see the hours upon hours of work I have to put in every week ON TOP of having a part time job just to keep everything running smoothly. 

When birds are returned I feel like a failure, what didn’t I see? Could I have changed the outcome somehow?? What could I have done better? How can I improve? 

Although I know these thoughts are normal, it is sometimes very hard to be kind to myself. I think we are all hard on ourselves to an extent but this month I’m really feeling it. 

But do you want to know what keeps me going? It’s all of you. You constantly show me that although there is bad in the world…there is also good. 

Thank you for always being there ❤️
Doing a partial behavioural assessment on Rhea

It’s no easy feat to get so many birds watching you at once for a group photo! 

What a lot of people don’t know about me and how I run my rescue is that I utilize a flock mentality when rehabbing birds. For the most part birds rely on a flock to keep themselves safe, it is hardwired into them to watch and learn from others of their species which I use to my advantage. 

Once birds are cleared medically, I try and integrate them into a flock setting so they can learn beneficial behaviours from their peers, they learn manners, how to coexist with others, how to interact with people and of course how to eat a good diet! When new birds watch me interact with other birds they learn that I’m not a threat but also learn how to interact properly with humans. There is often a little bit of squabbling, new birds may be defensive or territorial and sometimes my own flock will push back but my flock is fair and they know what I will and will not tolerate. 

I would not be able to do what I do without my two flocks, the conure flock who help me with larger birds, and the lovebird flock who helps with with my smaller rehabs or birds who are a little more scared as the smaller birds are rarely seen as a threat. 

I’m so proud of my birds, they don’t realize it but they help save a lot of lives. 

Below from left to right we have:
Yoshida aka Mama Yosh, below her a current rehab named Nexus, Mama Yosh’s mate Ronin, Jafar a current rehab, Tango and her bestie Osiris

Currently my little cousin is going through brain surgery, my aunt who provides most of the income for our family is with her at Sick kids London Ontario. If anyone would be able to help support our family during this time, a gofundme has been set up. Brigid is literally the light of all of our lives, and financially we are struggling…I’m not religious but please pray for us and if you cannot donate please share this around. Between the rescue and my lack of hours at work I really wish I could contribute more, but I can’t…I still want to help though.❤️ Thank you all so so much, If you would like to read more into it the link under my bio will take you to the Gofundme where my aunt goes more in depth on what’s been going on.
I’ve been working on my photography as of late ☺️ Sorry I’ve been so absent! A lot has been going on ❤️
